<br>
Besides tank mezzing, which features a tank controlling each extra mob while the primary focus of the raid is on another target, there is also 'root parking', which is a tactic many classes employ. This is where a mob with mediocre magic resistance can be immobilized by rooting it away from melee range of players. This mob then can be slowed and/or mesmerized by the appropriate classes when available.<br>
<br>
Be ready to get aggro on mobs that have been broken from their state of mesmerization. Sometimes, these mobs will make a beeline for the enchanters or shamans and not many melee classes will be able to take aggro in time before the mob kills a casting class. This is where through the use of your many stun spells, you quickly get to the top of the mob's hate list and take the place of the enchanter or shaman, even the designated main tank(s). Once you gain control of the mob, turn off your attack and do not hit taunt, let the designated tank slowly peel the agro away from you. Be careful, because gaining aggro from a distance can lead to the ping-pong effect, where the mob makes beeline after beeline to different characters and causes everyone to run around to get back in melee range.<br>
<br>
In situations where there is a Complete-Heal rotation being used on a group of designated main tanks, be ready to use your Lay Hands to cover the transfer of heals and tanking duties from one main tank to the next main tank. The few seconds between the transfer are crucial, and your 2000+ hitpoint instant heal can mean the different between the new main tank dying prematurely and breaking your raid, or the success of your raid. I recommend that Paladins invest in the 5 Alternate Advancement points it requires to turn your Lay Hands into a Complete Heal.<br>
<br>
Your Superior Heals and Celestial Cleansing, although highly ineffective for main tanks due to cast times and stacking issues, works great for patch healing casters. One of the best uses is to heal players who are using a Magician's 'mod rods', converting their hitpoints for more mana. Not only do you allow them room to work with as far as future mod rodding goes, you prevent any chances of them getting 'low health aggro' which could kill not only the person with low health, but the entire raid, if the mob has AE attacks and is now in line-of-sight of the once-hidden casters.<br>
 <br>
 <br>
 <br>
<br>
